Text: Today, we formed our project groups to embark on our personal journey to solving real world problems.
I feel anxious, but I realise that this is because this is all unknown territory.
So maybe it's a matter of anxiousness blurred with excitement because it is an opportunity to try something new.
What my group and I will be embarking on is to curate an app, that museum-goers can use during their visit to enhance their experience.
This mainly involves (I assume) scanning a variety of QR codes that would take the user to an informative youtube video or an informative part of the museum website.
If I were to be totally honest, the idea of scanning a QR code in an attempt to enhance the human experience sounded a tad flat to me.
I found myself wondering whether people still even used QR codes.
I came across a 5 min read (https: //medium.com/whitney-digital/qr-codes-alive-and-well-47115abd234), where the title of the article asks "QR codes:  Alive and Well in the Museum?".
Pertaining to the importance of the project, I read it.
The article talks about a trial that was started, by placing codes in a number of places throughout the museum.
The locations and numbers of respective scans between Nov 2018 and May 2019 were recorded and ultimately, the moral of the story is that, yes, people do still use QR codes.
An interesting aspect of the article that stood out to me was that, instead of building an app, a QR code was placed on the ticket that took the user to a website.
They brought up the fact that an app may not necessarily encourage users to use their own devices because it required a downloading process.
It makes sense, because it is likely the experience would be a one- off visit.
Sooo, maybe for this project, we could do something similar?
I guess we will have to see.
